habitat: S-facing bank of arroyo. Chihuahuan Desert Scrub with Acacia greggii, Yucca torreyi, Opuntia imbricata, Tecoma stans, Brickellia, and Guaiacum. Rounded spiny shrub 1.5 m. tall. Dominant shrub on edge of terrace above Palillos Arroyo. Corolla reddish, stamens yellow. Crowded w. bees.
locality: Chinati Mtns State Natural Area. Pelillos Arroyo, a major drainage on the SW side of the Chinati Mts.

habitat: Igneous boulders and alluvium at edge of arroyo. S-facing bank of arroyo; Chihuahuan Desert Scrub w/ Acacia greggii, Yucca torreyi, Opuntia imbricata, Tecoma stans, Brickellia, Guaiacum.
locality: Chinati Mountains State Natural Area. Pelillos Arroyo, a major drainage on the SW side of the Chinati Mountains.

locality: Chinati Mtns State Natural Area. Pelillos Arroyo, a major drainage on the SW side of the Chinati Mts.

habitat: Igneous boulders and alluvium at edge of arroyo. S-facing bank of arroyo. Chihuahuan Desert Scrub w. Acacia greggii, Yucca torreyi, Opuntia imbricata, Tecoma stans, Brickellia and Guaiacum. Erect, thickly-branched perennial 15 cm high from woody rootstock.
locality: Chinati Mtns. Natural Area. Pelillos Arroyo, a major drainage on the SW side of the Chinati Mtns.

habitat: S-facing bank of arroyo. Chihuahuan Desert Scrub with Acacia greggii, Yucca torreyi, Opuntia imbricata, Tecoma stans, Brickellia, Porophyllum scoparium, and Guaiacum. habitat: S-facing bank of arroyo. Chihuahuan Desert Scrub with Acacia greggii, Yucca torreyi, Opuntia imbricata, Tecoma stans, Brickellia, Porophyllum scoparium, and Guaiacum. Erect perennial in alluvium. Fls lavender. Fairly common.
locality: Chinati Mtns State Natural Area. Pelillos Arroyo, a major drainage on the SW side of the Chinati Mts.

habitat: Igneous boulders and alluvium at edge of arroyo. S-facing bank of arroyo. Chihuahuan Desert Scrub w. Acacia greggii, Yucca torreyi, Opuntia imbricata, Tecoma stans, Brickellia and Guaiacum. Erect perennial from woody roots. Fls lavender.

habitat: Igneous boulders and alluvium at edge of arroyo. S-facing bank of arroyo. Chihuahuan Desert Scrub w. Acacia greggii, Yucca torreyi, Opuntia imbricata, Tecoma stans, Brickellia and Guaiacum. habitat: S-facing bank of arroyo. Chihuahuan Desert Scrub with Acacia greggii, Yucca torreyi, Opuntia imbricata, Tecoma stans, Brickellia, Porophyllum scoparium, and Guaiacum. Erect many-stemmed perennial from woody base 50 cm tall. Fls open at 1200 hrs. Pink & fading to red-pink.

habitat: S-facing bank of arroyo. Chihuahuan Desert Scrub with Acacia greggii, Yucca torreyi, Opuntia imbricata, Tecoma stans, Brickellia, and Guaiacum. Erect, much-branched glaucous subshrub 50 cm tall. Latex white. Fls dusty pink. Common in arroyos.

habitat: Igneous boulders and alluvium at edge of arroyo. S-facing bank of arroyo. Chihuahuan Desert Scrub w. Acacia greggii, Yucca torreyi, Opuntia imbricata, Tacoma stans, Brickellia, and Guaiacum. habitat: In grassland on loamy soils on broad flat landscape underlain by a mix of Perdiz Conglomerate (a fanglomerate of variable composition) and Quaternary alluvium. habitat: Ocassional in light-colored sandy mineral soil among light gray igneous rock on gentle slope of low rocky hill supporting open shrubland. Yucca elata and Ephedra sp. dominant on slope; Larrea tridentata and Parthenium incanum dominant on flat top. Other associates include Condalia ericoides, Croton pottsii, Dalea formosa, Dyschoriste decumbens, Dyssodia acerosa, Eriogonum abertianum, Euphorbia lata, E. revoluta, Hilaria swallenii, Lesquerella fendleri, Melampodium leucanthum, Nolina texana, Prosopis glandulosa var. torreyana, Psilostrophe tagetina, Tiquilia canescens, Verbena neomexicana, and Zinnia grandiflora.
locality: W side of main road on Hip-O Ranch Preserve (TNC). 0.6 -0.7 mi. N of gate at railroad track, ca. 5-6 airmiles WNW of Marfa. Marfa Quadrangle.

habitat: In patches of relatively sparse vegetation within shrubland on outcrops of chalk-like tuff or tuffaceous sandstone of the Tascotal Formation exposed on slopes. Matrix vegetation a shrubland dominated by Acacia neovernicosa, Larrea tridentata. Other associates included Bahia absinthifolia, Bouteloua cf. aristidoides, B. cf. hirsuta, Calliandra iselyi, Dasyochloa pulchella, Echinocactus horizonthalonius, Enneapogon desvauxii, Fouquieria splendens, Hedeoma 31789, Hibiscus denudatus, Pectis sp., Polygala 31785, Psathyrotopsis scaposa, Talinopsis frutescens, Tiquilia greggii.
locality: N side of a major E-W internal road just W of camp on old ranch HQ, ca. 1.9-2.0 airmiles ESE of St. Rt. 169 bridge over Alamito Creek just N of Plata. Kennedy Ranch (Dixon Water Foundation). Puerto Potrillo Quadrangle.

habitat: At base of seep on W-facing canyon wall w. habitat: In grassland on somewhat gravelly gentle slope on very gently rolling landscape underlain by a mix of Perdiz Conglomerate (a fanglomerate of variable composition) and Quaternary alluvium. Common components of grassland included Bouteloua gracilis, Aristida adscencionis. Other associates included Amaranthus palmeri, Aristida longiseta, Asclepias brachystephana, Atriplex elegans, Berlandiera lyrata, Boerhavia sp., Bothriochloa laguroides, Bouteloua barbata, B. curtipendula, Buddleja scordioides, Chamaesyce serpyllifolia, Croton pottsii, Cucurbita foetidissima, Enneapogon desvauxii, Eryngium heterophyllum, Evolvulus sp., Hilaria swallenii, Kallstroemia parviflora, Melampodium leucanthum, Panicum obtusum, Prosopis glandulosa, Psilostrophe tagetina, Salsola sp., Solanum elaeagnifolium, Tidestroemia lanuginosa, Zinnia grandiflora.
locality: Near windmill just N of house and barns, ca. 0.8-0.9 airmiles N to NNW of jct. US Rt. 90 and St. Rt. 17 in downtown Marfa. Southeast corner of Mimms Ranch (Dixon Water Foundation). Marfa Quadrangle.
